extern "C" {
    #[doc = "Allocates a  storage instance.  It is  largely the same as  system malloc(),"]
    #[doc = "except:"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- It raises Ruby exceptions instead of returning NULL, and"]
    #[doc = "- In case of `ENOMEM` it tries to GC to make some room."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `in` size            Requested amount of memory."]
    #[doc = "- **@exception** [`rb_eNoMemError`]  No space left for `size` bytes allocation."]
    #[doc = "- **@return** A valid pointer  to an allocated storage instance;  which has at"]
    #[doc = "least `size` bytes width, with appropriate alignment detected by"]
    #[doc = "the underlying malloc() routine."]
    #[doc = "---\n ### Note\nIt doesn't return NULL."]
    #[doc = "---\n ### Note\nUnlike some malloc() implementations, it allocates something and"]
    #[doc = "returns a meaningful value even when `size` is equal to zero."]
    #[doc = "---\n ### Warning\nThe return  value shall  be invalidated  exactly once  by either"]
    #[doc = "ruby_xfree(),  ruby_xrealloc(), or  ruby_xrealloc2().   It is  a"]
    #[doc = "failure to pass it to system free(), because the system and Ruby"]
    #[doc = "might or might not share the same malloc() implementation."]
    #[doc = "\n---\n\nGenerated by [rb-sys](https://github.com/oxidize-rb/rb-sys) for Ruby 3.2.0"]
    pub fn ruby_xmalloc(size: size_t) -> *mut ::core::ffi::c_void;
}
extern "C" {
    #[doc = "Identical to ruby_xmalloc(), except it allocates `nelems` * `elemsiz` bytes."]
    #[doc = "This is needed  because the multiplication could integer  overflow.  On such"]
    #[doc = "situations  Ruby does  not try  to  allocate at  all but  raises Ruby  level"]
    #[doc = "exceptions  instead.  If  there  is  no integer  overflow  the behaviour  is"]
    #[doc = "exactly the same as `ruby_xmalloc(nelems*elemsiz)`."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `in` nelems          Number of elements."]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `in` elemsiz         Size of an element."]
    #[doc = "- **@exception** [`rb_eNoMemError`]  No space left for allocation."]
    #[doc = "- **@exception** [`rb_eArgError`]    `nelems` * `elemsiz` would overflow."]
    #[doc = "- **@return** A valid pointer  to an allocated storage instance;  which has at"]
    #[doc = "least  `nelems`  *  `elemsiz`   bytes  width,  with  appropriate"]
    #[doc = "alignment detected by the underlying malloc() routine."]
    #[doc = "---\n ### Note\nIt doesn't return NULL."]
    #[doc = "---\n ### Note\nUnlike some malloc() implementations, it allocates something and"]
    #[doc = "returns a  meaningful value even  when `nelems` or  `elemsiz` or"]

    #[doc = "---\n ### Warning\nThe return  value shall  be invalidated  exactly once  by either"]
    #[doc = "ruby_xfree(),  ruby_xrealloc(), or  ruby_xrealloc2().   It is  a"]

extern "C" {
    #[doc = "Defines an undef of a method.  -- What?"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "In ruby, there are two separate concepts called \\\"undef\\\" and \\\"remove_method\\\"."]
    #[doc = "The thing you imagine when you  \\\"un-define\\\" a method is remove_method.  This"]
    #[doc = "one on the  other hand is masking of a  previous method definition.  Suppose"]
    #[doc = "for instance:"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "```ruby"]
    #[doc = "class Foo"]
    #[doc = "def foo"]
    #[doc = "end"]
    #[doc = "end"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "class Bar < Foo"]
    #[doc = "def bar"]
    #[doc = "foo"]
    #[doc = "end"]
    #[doc = "end"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "class Baz < Foo"]
    #[doc = "undef foo            # <--- (*1)"]
    #[doc = "end"]
    #[doc = "```"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "This `undef foo` at `(*1)` must not eliminate `Foo#foo`, because that method"]
    #[doc = "is also used from `Bar#bar`.  So  instead of physically executing the target"]
    #[doc = "method, `undef` inserts  a special filtering entry to the  class (`Baz` this"]
    #[doc = "case).  That entry,  when called, acts as  if there were no  methods at all."]
    #[doc = "But the original can still be accessible, via ways like `Bar#bar` above."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `out` klass            The class to insert an undef."]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `in` name             Name of the undef."]
    #[doc = "- **@exception** [`rb_eTypeError`]    `klass` is a non-module."]
    #[doc = "- **@exception** [`rb_eFrozenError`]  `klass` is frozen."]
    #[doc = "- **@see** [`rb_remove_method`]"]
    #[doc = "\n---\n\nGenerated by [rb-sys](https://github.com/oxidize-rb/rb-sys) for Ruby 3.2.0"]
    pub fn rb_undef_method(klass: VALUE, name: *const ::std::os::raw::c_char);
}

    #[doc = "Retrieves argument from argc and  argv to given ::VALUE references according"]
    #[doc = "to the format string.  The format can be described in ABNF as follows:"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "```"]
    #[doc = "scan-arg-spec  := param-arg-spec [keyword-arg-spec] [block-arg-spec]"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "param-arg-spec        := pre-arg-spec [post-arg-spec] / post-arg-spec /"]
    #[doc = "pre-opt-post-arg-spec"]
    #[doc = "pre-arg-spec          := num-of-leading-mandatory-args"]
    #[doc = "[num-of-optional-args]"]
    #[doc = "post-arg-spec         := sym-for-variable-length-args"]
    #[doc = "[num-of-trailing-mandatory-args]"]
    #[doc = "pre-opt-post-arg-spec := num-of-leading-mandatory-args num-of-optional-args"]
    #[doc = "num-of-trailing-mandatory-args"]
    #[doc = "keyword-arg-spec      := sym-for-keyword-arg"]
    #[doc = "block-arg-spec        := sym-for-block-arg"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "num-of-leading-mandatory-args  := DIGIT ; The number of leading mandatory"]
    #[doc = "; arguments"]
    #[doc = "num-of-optional-args           := DIGIT ; The number of optional arguments"]
    #[doc = "sym-for-variable-length-args   := \\\"*\\\"   ; Indicates that variable length"]
    #[doc = ";  arguments are captured as a ruby"]
    #[doc = "; array"]
    #[doc = "num-of-trailing-mandatory-args := DIGIT ; The number of trailing mandatory"]
    #[doc = "; arguments"]

    #[doc = "sym-for-block-arg              := \\\"&\\\"   ; Indicates that an iterator block"]
    #[doc = "; should be captured if given"]

    #[doc = "\n"]

extern "C" {
    #[doc = "Exports an integer into a buffer.   This function fills the buffer specified"]
    #[doc = "by `words`  and `numwords` as `val`  in the format specified  by `wordsize`,"]
    #[doc = "`nails` and `flags`."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `in` val            Integer   or  integer-like   object  which   has"]
    #[doc = "`#to_int` method."]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `out` words          Return buffer."]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `in` numwords       Number of words of `words`."]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `in` wordsize       Number of bytes per word."]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `in` nails          Number  of   padding  bits  in  a   word.   Most"]
    #[doc = "significant nails  bits of each word  are filled"]
    #[doc = "by zero."]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `in` flags          Bitwise  or  of   constants  whose  name  starts"]
    #[doc = "\\\"INTEGER_PACK_\\\"."]
    #[doc = "- **@exception** [`rb_eTypeError`]  `val` doesn't respond to `#to_int`."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "Possible flags are:"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- #INTEGER_PACK_MSWORD_FIRST:"]
    #[doc = "Stores the most significant word as the first word."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- #INTEGER_PACK_LSWORD_FIRST:"]
    #[doc = "Stores the least significant word as the first word."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- #INTEGER_PACK_MSBYTE_FIRST:"]
    #[doc = "Stores the most  significant byte in a  word as the first  byte in the"]
    #[doc = "word."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- #INTEGER_PACK_LSBYTE_FIRST:"]
    #[doc = "Stores the least significant  byte in a word as the  first byte in the"]
    #[doc = "word."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- #INTEGER_PACK_NATIVE_BYTE_ORDER:"]
    #[doc = "Either   #INTEGER_PACK_MSBYTE_FIRST    or   #INTEGER_PACK_LSBYTE_FIRST"]
    #[doc = "corresponding to the host's endian."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- #INTEGER_PACK_2COMP:"]
    #[doc = "Uses 2's complement representation."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- #INTEGER_PACK_LITTLE_ENDIAN: Shorthand of"]
    #[doc = "`INTEGER_PACK_LSWORD_FIRST|INTEGER_PACK_LSBYTE_FIRST`."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- #INTEGER_PACK_BIG_ENDIAN: Shorthand of"]
    #[doc = "`INTEGER_PACK_MSWORD_FIRST|INTEGER_PACK_MSBYTE_FIRST`."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- #INTEGER_PACK_FORCE_GENERIC_IMPLEMENTATION:"]
    #[doc = "Uses generic implementation (for test and debug)."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "This  function  fills  the  buffer  specified  by  `words`  as  `val`'s  2's"]
    #[doc = "complement representation  if #INTEGER_PACK_2COMP  is specified  in `flags`."]
    #[doc = "Otherwise it fills `words` as `abs(val)`  and signedness is returned via the"]
    #[doc = "return value."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- **@return** The  signedness and  overflow  condition.   The overflow  condition"]
    #[doc = "depends on #INTEGER_PACK_2COMP."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "When #INTEGER_PACK_2COMP is not specified:"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- `-2` :"]
    #[doc = "Negative overflow.  `val <= -2**(numwords*(wordsize*CHAR_BIT-nails))`"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- `-1` :"]
    #[doc = "Negative without overflow."]
    #[doc = "`-2**(numwords*(wordsize*CHAR_BIT-nails)) < val < 0`"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- `0` : zero.  `val == 0`"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- `1` :"]
    #[doc = "Positive without overflow."]
    #[doc = "`0 < val < 2**(numwords*(wordsize*CHAR_BIT-nails))`"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- `2` :"]
    #[doc = "Positive overflow.  `2**(numwords*(wordsize*CHAR_BIT-nails)) <= val`"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "When #INTEGER_PACK_2COMP is specified:"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- `-2` :"]
    #[doc = "Negative overflow.  `val < -2**(numwords*(wordsize*CHAR_BIT-nails))`"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- `-1` :"]
    #[doc = "Negative without overflow."]
    #[doc = "`-2**(numwords*(wordsize*CHAR_BIT-nails)) <= val < 0`"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- `0` : zero.  `val == 0`"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- `1` :"]
    #[doc = "Positive without overflow."]
    #[doc = "`0 < val < 2**(numwords*(wordsize*CHAR_BIT-nails))`"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- `2` :"]
    #[doc = "Positive overflow.  `2**(numwords*(wordsize*CHAR_BIT-nails)) <= val`"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "The value,  `-2**(numwords*(wordsize*CHAR_BIT-nails))`, is  representable in"]
    #[doc = "2's complement representation  but not representable in  absolute value.  So"]
    #[doc = "`-1`  is returned  for the  value  if #INTEGER_PACK_2COMP  is specified  but"]
    #[doc = "returns `-2` if #INTEGER_PACK_2COMP is not specified."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "The least significant words are filled in the buffer when overflow occur."]
    #[doc = "\n---\n\nGenerated by [rb-sys](https://github.com/oxidize-rb/rb-sys) for Ruby 3.2.0"]
    pub fn rb_integer_pack(
        val: VALUE,
        words: *mut ::core::ffi::c_void,
        numwords: size_t,
        wordsize: size_t,
        nails: size_t,
        flags: ::std::os::raw::c_int,

    #[doc = "suspended much like in a call to [`rb_fiber_yield`]."]
    #[doc = "\n"]

    #[doc = "call.  Arguments passed to transfer are treated like those passed to resume."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "The two style of control passing to and from fiber (one is [`rb_fiber_resume`]"]
    #[doc = "and  [`rb_fiber_yield`], another  is  [`rb_fiber_transfer`] to  and from  fiber)"]
    #[doc = "can't be freely mixed."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- If the  Fiber's lifecycle had  started with  transfer, it will  never be"]
    #[doc = "able to  yield or be  resumed control  passing, only finish  or transfer"]
    #[doc = "back.   (It  still can  resume  other  fibers  that  are allowed  to  be"]
    #[doc = "resumed.)"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- If  the Fiber's  lifecycle  had started  with resume,  it  can yield  or"]
    #[doc = "transfer to  another Fiber, but  can receive  control back only  the way"]
    #[doc = "compatible with  the way it  was given away:  if it had  transferred, it"]
    #[doc = "only can  be transferred  back, and if  it had yielded,  it only  can be"]
    #[doc = "resumed back.  After that, it again can transfer or yield."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "If those rules are broken, [`rb_eFiberError`] is raised."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "For an  individual Fiber design,  yield/resume is  easier to use  (the Fiber"]
    #[doc = "just gives away control,  it doesn't need to think about  who the control is"]
    #[doc = "given to),  while transfer is more  flexible for complex cases,  allowing to"]
    #[doc = "build arbitrary graphs of Fibers dependent on each other."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `out` fiber           Explicit control destination."]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `in` argc            Number of objects of `argv`."]

extern "C" {
    #[doc = "Maybe this  is the only  function provided for  C extensions to  control the"]
    #[doc = "pinning of objects, so  let us describe it in detail.   These days Ruby's GC"]
    #[doc = "is copying.  As far as an object's physical address is guaranteed unused, it"]
    #[doc = "can move  around the object space.   Our GC engine rearranges  these objects"]
    #[doc = "after it  reclaims unreachable objects  from our  object space, so  that the"]
    #[doc = "space  is   compact  (improves  memory   locality).   This  is   called  the"]
    #[doc = "\\\"compaction\\\" phase, and works  well most of the time... as  far as there are"]
    #[doc = "no C  extensions.  C  extensions complicate the  scenario because  Ruby core"]
    #[doc = "cannot detect  any use  of the  physical address  of an  object inside  of C"]
    #[doc = "functions.  In order to prevent  memory corruptions, objects observable from"]
    #[doc = "C extensions are \\\"pinned\\\"; they stick to where they are born until they die,"]
    #[doc = "just in  case any C  extensions touch their  raw pointers.  This  variant of"]
    #[doc = "scheme  is   called  \\\"Mostly-Copying\\\"  garbage  collector.    Authors  of  C"]
    #[doc = "extensions,  however,   can  extremely   carefully  write  them   to  become"]
    #[doc = "compaction-aware.  To do so avoid referring  to a Ruby object from inside of"]
    #[doc = "your struct  in the  first place.   But if  that is  not possible,  use this"]
    #[doc = "function  from your  ::[`rb_data_type_struct`]::dmark  then.   This way  objects"]
    #[doc = "marked using it are  considered movable.  If you chose this  way you have to"]
    #[doc = "manually fix up locations of such moved pointers using [`rb_gc_location`]."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- **@see** Bartlett,  Joel  F.,  \\\"Compacting Garbage  Collection  with  Ambiguous"]
    #[doc = "Roots\\\",  ACM  SIGPLAN  Lisp  Pointers  Volume  1  Issue  6  pp.  3-12,"]
    #[doc = "April-May-June, 1988. <https://doi.org/10.1145/1317224.1317225>"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `in` obj  Object that is movable."]
    #[doc = "- **@post** Values stored in `tbl` are marked."]
    #[doc = "\n---\n\nGenerated by [rb-sys](https://github.com/oxidize-rb/rb-sys) for Ruby 3.2.0"]

extern "C" {
    #[doc = "Marshal  format compatibility  layer.  Over  time, classes  evolve, so  that"]
    #[doc = "their internal data structure change  drastically.  For instance an instance"]
    #[doc = "of ::[`rb_cRange`]  was made  of ::RUBY_T_OBJECT  in 1.x.,  but in  3.x it  is a"]
    #[doc = "::RUBY_T_STRUCT now.  In  order to keep binary compatibility,  we \\\"fake\\\" the"]
    #[doc = "marshalled representation to stick to old  types.  This is the API to enable"]
    #[doc = "that manoeuvre.  Here is how:"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "First, because  you are going to  keep backwards compatibility, you  need to"]
    #[doc = "retain the old implementation of your  class.  Rename it, and keep the class"]
    #[doc = "somewhere  (for  instance  [`rb_register_global_address`] could  help).   Next"]
    #[doc = "create your new class.  Do whatever you want."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "Then, this is the key point.  Create two new \\\"bridge\\\" functions that convert"]
    #[doc = "the structs back and forth:"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- the  \\\"dumper\\\" function  that takes  an instance  of the  new class,  and"]
    #[doc = "returns   an  instance   of  the   old   one.   This   is  called   from"]
    #[doc = "[`rb_marshal_dump`], to keep it possible for old programs to read your new"]
    #[doc = "data."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- the \\\"loader\\\" function that takes two  arguments, new one and old one, in"]
    #[doc = "that  order.  [`rb_marshal_load`]  calls  this function  when  it finds  a"]
    #[doc = "representation of  the retained old class.   The old one passed  to this"]
    #[doc = "function   is   the   reconstructed   instance   of   the   old   class."]
    #[doc = "Reverse-engineer  that to  modify the  new  one, to  have the  identical"]
    #[doc = "contents."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "Finally, connect all of them using this function."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `in` newclass       The class that needs conversion."]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `in` oldclass       Old implementation of `newclass`."]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `in` dumper         Function that converts `newclass` to `oldclass`."]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `in` loader         Function that converts `oldclass` to `newclass`."]
    #[doc = "- **@exception** [`rb_eTypeError`]  `newclass` has no allocator."]
    #[doc = "\n---\n\nGenerated by [rb-sys](https://github.com/oxidize-rb/rb-sys) for Ruby 3.2.0"]
    pub fn rb_marshal_define_compat(
        newclass: VALUE,
        oldclass: VALUE,
        dumper: ::core::option::Option<unsafe extern "C" fn(arg1: VALUE) -> VALUE>,
        loader: ::core::option::Option<unsafe extern "C" fn(arg1: VALUE, arg2: VALUE) -> VALUE>,
    );
}

extern "C" {
    #[doc = "\\\"Detaches\\\"  a subprocess.   In POSIX  systems every  child processes  that a"]
    #[doc = "process creates must be `wait(2)`-ed.  A child process that died yet has not"]
    #[doc = "been  waited so  far  is called  a  \\\"zombie\\\", which  more  or less  consumes"]
    #[doc = "resources.   This function  automates reclamation  of such  processes.  Once"]
    #[doc = "after this function successfully returns  you can basically forget about the"]
    #[doc = "child process."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `in` pid  Process to wait."]
    #[doc = "- **@return** An instance of ::[`rb_cThread`] which is `waitpid(2)`-ing `pid`."]
    #[doc = "- **@post** You can just forget about the return value.  GC reclaims it."]
    #[doc = "- **@post** You  can  know the  exit  status  by  querying `#value`  of  the"]
    #[doc = "return value (which is a blocking operation)."]

extern "C" {
    #[doc = "Sends a signal (\\\"kills\\\") to processes."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "The first argument is the signal, either in:"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- Numerical representation (e.g. `9`), or"]
    #[doc = "- Textual  representation   of  canonical   (e.g.   `:SIGKILL`)   name  or"]
    #[doc = "abbreviated (e.g. `:KILL`) name, either in ::[`rb_cSymbol`] or ::[`rb_cString`]."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "All the  remaining arguments are  numerical representations of  process IDs."]
    #[doc = "This function iterates over them to send the specified signal."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "You can specify both negative PIDs and negative signo to this function:"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "```"]
    #[doc = "sig \\\\ pid | >= 1 | == 0 | == -1 | <= -2"]
    #[doc = "===========+======+======+=======+======="]
    #[doc = "> 0   |  #1  |  #2  |  #3   |  #4"]
    #[doc = "== 0   |  #5  |  #6  |  #7   |  #8"]
    #[doc = "< 0   |  #9  |  #10 |      #11"]
    #[doc = "```"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- Case #1: When  signo and PID are both positive,  this function sends the"]
    #[doc = "specified signal to the specified process (intuitive)."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- Case #2: When  signo is  positive and PID  is zero, this  function sends"]
    #[doc = "that signal to the current process group."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- Case #3: When signo is positive and  PID is -1, this function sends that"]
    #[doc = "signal to everything that the current process is allowed to kill."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- Case #4: When signo  is positive and PID is negative  (but not -1), this"]
    #[doc = "function sends that signal to every  processes in a process group, whose"]
    #[doc = "process group ID is the absolute value of the passed PID."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- Case #5: When  signo  is zero  and PID is  positive, this  function just"]
    #[doc = "checks  for the  existence of  the  specified process  and doesn't  send"]
    #[doc = "anything to  anyone.  In  case the process  is absent  `Errno::ESRCH` is"]
    #[doc = "raised."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- Case #6: When signo and PID are  both zero, this function checks for the"]
    #[doc = "existence of the current process group.   And it must do.  This function"]
    #[doc = "is effectively a no-op then."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- Case #7: When signo is zero and PID is -1, this function checks if there"]
    #[doc = "is any other  process that the current process can  kill.  At least init"]
    #[doc = "(PID 1) must exist, so this must not fail."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- Case #8: When  signo is  zero and  PID is  negative (but  not -1),  this"]
    #[doc = "function checks  if there is a  process group whose process  group ID is"]
    #[doc = "the absolute  value of  the passed  PID.  In case  the process  group is"]
    #[doc = "absent `Errno::ESRCH` is raised."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- Case #9: When signo is negative and PID is positive, this function sends"]
    #[doc = "the absolute value of the passed signo to the process group specified as"]
    #[doc = "the PID."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- Case #10: When signo is negative and  PID is zero, it is highly expected"]
    #[doc = "that this function  sends the absolute value of the  passed signo to the"]
    #[doc = "current  process   group.   Strictly  speaking,  IEEE   Std  1003.1-2017"]
    #[doc = "specifies that  this (`killpg(3posix)` with  an argument of zero)  is an"]
    #[doc = "undefined behaviour.  But no operating system  is known so far that does"]
    #[doc = "things differently."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- Case #11: When  signo and PID  are both negative, the  behaviour of this"]
    #[doc = "function  depends on  how `killpg(3)`  works.  On  Linux, it  seems such"]
    #[doc = "attempt is  strictly prohibited and  `Errno::EINVAL` is raised.   But on"]
    #[doc = "macOS, it seems it  tries to to send the signal  actually to the process"]
    #[doc = "group."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "---\n ### Note\nAbove description is in fact different from how `kill(2)` works."]
    #[doc = "We interpret the passed arguments before passing them through to"]
    #[doc = "system calls."]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `in` argc                 Number of objects in `argv`."]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `in` argv                 Signal, followed by target PIDs."]
    #[doc = "- **@exception** [`rb_eArgError`]         Unknown signal name."]
    #[doc = "- **@exception** [`rb_eSystemCallError`]  Various errors sending signal to processes."]
    #[doc = "- **@return** Something numeric.  The meaning of this return value is unclear."]
    #[doc = "It seems in case of #1 above, this could be the body count.  But"]
    #[doc = "other cases remain mysterious."]
    #[doc = "\n---\n\nGenerated by [rb-sys](https://github.com/oxidize-rb/rb-sys) for Ruby 3.2.0"]
    pub fn rb_f_kill(argc: ::std::os::raw::c_int, argv: *const VALUE) -> VALUE;

#[doc = "This is  the type of UBFs.   An UBF is  a function that unblocks  a blocking"]
#[doc = "region.  For instance when a thread is blocking due to `pselect(3posix)`, it"]
#[doc = "is highly expected that `pthread_kill(3posix)` can interrupt the system call"]
#[doc = "and  the  thread  could  revive.   Or  when a  thread  is  blocking  due  to"]
#[doc = "`waitpid(3posix)`, it  is highly  expected that  killing the  waited process"]
#[doc = "should suffice.  An UBF is a function that does such things.  Designing your"]
#[doc = "own UBF  needs deep understanding  of why  your blocking region  blocks, how"]
#[doc = "threads work in ruby, and a matter of luck.  It often is the case you simply"]
#[doc = "cannot cancel something that had already begun."]
#[doc = "\n"]
#[doc = "- **@see** [`rb_thread_call_without_gvl`]"]

extern "C" {
    #[doc = "Registers a postponed job."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "There  are situations  when running  a ruby  program is  not possible.   For"]
    #[doc = "instance when  a program is in  a signal handler; for  another instance when"]
    #[doc = "the GC  is busy.   On such situations  however, there might  be needs  to do"]
    #[doc = "something.  We cannot but defer such operations until we are 100% sure it is"]
    #[doc = "safe  to execute  them.   This  mechanism is  called  postponed jobs.   This"]
    #[doc = "function  registers a  new one.   The registered  job would  eventually gets"]
    #[doc = "executed."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `in` flags      (Unused) reserved for future extensions."]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `in` func       Job body."]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `in,out` data       Passed as-is to `func`."]
    #[doc = "- **@retval** 0          Postponed job buffer is full.  Failed."]

    #[doc = "encodings.  Encoding  conversion are  has_and_belongs_to_many relationships."]
    #[doc = "There could be no direct conversion defined for the passed pair.  Ruby tries"]
    #[doc = "to find  an indirect  way to  do so  then.  For  instance ISO-8859-1  has no"]
    #[doc = "direct  conversion  to  ISO-2022-JP.   But  there  is  ISO-8859-1  to  UTF-8"]

extern "C" {
    #[doc = "Finds or creates  a stdio's file structure  from a Ruby's one.   This can be"]
    #[doc = "handy if you want to call an external API that accepts `FILE *`."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "---\n ### Note\nNote however, that `FILE`s can  have their own buffer.  Mixing Ruby's"]
    #[doc = "and stdio's file are basically dangerous.  Use with care."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- **@param** `in,out` fptr  Target IO."]
    #[doc = "- **@return** A stdio's file, created if absent."]
    #[doc = "- **@post** `fptr` has its corresponding stdio's file."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "---\n ### Internal\n"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "We had rich support  for `FILE` before!  In the days  of 1.8.x ::[`rb_io_t`] was"]
    #[doc = "like this:"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "```CXX"]
    #[doc = "typedef struct [`rb_io_t`] {"]
    #[doc = "FILE *f;                    // stdio ptr for read/write"]
    #[doc = "FILE *f2;                   // additional ptr for rw pipes"]
    #[doc = "int mode;                   // mode flags"]
    #[doc = "int pid;                    // child's pid (for pipes)"]
    #[doc = "int lineno;                 // number of lines read"]
    #[doc = "char *path;                 // pathname for file"]
    #[doc = "void (*finalize) _((struct [`rb_io_t`]*,int)); // finalize proc"]
    #[doc = "} [`rb_io_t`];"]
    #[doc = "```"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "But we  eventually abandoned this layout.   It was too difficult.   We could"]
    #[doc = "not have fine-grained control over the `f` field."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- `FILE` tends  to be  an opaque  struct.  It does  not interface  well with"]
    #[doc = "`select(2)` etc.   This makes  IO multiplexing  quite hard.   Using stdio,"]
    #[doc = "there is arguably no portable way to know if `fwrite(3)` blocks."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- Nonblocking  mode,  which   is  another  core  concept   that  enables  IO"]
    #[doc = "multiplexing, does not interface with stdio routines at all."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- Detection of duplexed IO is also hard for the same reason."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- `feof(3)` is not portable."]
    #[doc = "<https://mail.python.org/pipermail/python-dev/2001-January/011390.html>"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- Solaris was a thing  back then.  They could not have  more than 256 `FILE`"]
    #[doc = "structures  at  a  time.   Their   file  descriptors  ware  stored  in  an"]
    #[doc = "`unsigned char`."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "- It is next to impossible to avoid  SEGV, especially when a thread tries to"]
    #[doc = "`ungetc(3)`-ing from a `FILE` which is `fread(3)`-ed by another one."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "In short, it is a bad idea to let someone else manage IO buffers, especially"]
    #[doc = "someone  you cannot  control.   This still  applies  to extension  libraries"]
    #[doc = "methinks.  Ruby doesn't prevent you from  shooting yourself in the foot, but"]
    #[doc = "consider yourself warned here."]
    #[doc = "\n---\n\nGenerated by [rb-sys](https://github.com/oxidize-rb/rb-sys) for Ruby 3.2.0"]

extern "C" {
    #[doc = "Queries the tied IO  for writing.  An IO can be  duplexed.  Fine.  The thing"]
    #[doc = "is,  that characteristics  could  sometimes be  achieved  by the  underlying"]
    #[doc = "operating  system (for  instance  a  socket's duplexity  is  by nature)  but"]
    #[doc = "sometimes  by us.   Notable example  is a  bidirectional pipe.   Suppose you"]
    #[doc = "have:"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "```ruby"]
    #[doc = "fp = IO.popen(\\\"-\\\", \\\"r+\\\")"]
    #[doc = "```"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "This pipe  is duplexed (the  `\\\"r+\\\"`).  You can  both read from/write  to it."]
    #[doc = "However your operating system may  or may not implement bidirectional pipes."]
    #[doc = "FreeBSD is one  of such operating systems  known to have one;  OTOH Linux is"]
    #[doc = "known  to lack  such  things.   So to  achieve  maximum portability,  Ruby's"]

    #[doc = "Instructs the OS to put its internal file structure into \\\"nonblocking mode\\\"."]
    #[doc = "This is  an in-Kernel concept.   Reading from/writing  to that file  using C"]
    #[doc = "function calls would return  -1 with errno set.  However when  it comes to a"]
    #[doc = "ruby program,  we hide that error  behind our `IO#read` method.   Ruby level"]
    #[doc = "`IO#read` blocks  regardless of this flag.   If you want to  avoid blocking,"]
    #[doc = "you should consider using methods like `IO#readpartial`."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "```ruby"]

    #[doc = "STDIN.nonblock = true"]
    #[doc = "STDIN.gets # blocks."]
    #[doc = "```"]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "As of  writing there is  a room  of this API  in Fiber schedulers.   A Fiber"]
    #[doc = "scheduler could be written in a  way its behaviour depends on this property."]
    #[doc = "You  need an  in-depth  understanding  of how  schedulers  work to  properly"]
    #[doc = "leverage this, though."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "---\n ### Note\nNote   however  that   nonblocking-ness  propagates   across  process"]
    #[doc = "boundaries.  You must  really carefully watch your  step when turning"]
    #[doc = "for  instance `stderr`  into nonblock  mode  (it tends  to be  shared"]
    #[doc = "across many  processes).  Also  it is  a complete  disaster to  mix a"]
    #[doc = "nonblocking file and stdio, and `stderr` tends to be under control of"]
    #[doc = "stdio in other processes."]

extern "C" {
    #[doc = "ruby_vm_at_exit registers a function _func_ to be invoked when a VM"]
    #[doc = "passed away.  Functions registered this way runs in reverse order"]
    #[doc = "of registration, just like END {} block does.  The difference is"]
    #[doc = "its timing to be triggered. ruby_vm_at_exit functions runs when a"]
    #[doc = "VM _passed_ _away_, while END {} blocks runs just _before_ a VM"]
    #[doc = "_is_ _passing_ _away_."]
    #[doc = "\n"]
    #[doc = "You cannot register a function to another VM than where you are in."]
    #[doc = "So where to register is intuitive, omitted.  OTOH the argument"]
    #[doc = "_func_ cannot know which VM it is in because at the time of"]
    #[doc = "invocation, the VM has already died and there is no execution"]
    #[doc = "context.  The VM itself is passed as the first argument to it."]
